### Spring Boot Flyway Demo API Tests

### 1. Get all users
GET http://localhost:8080/api/users
Accept: application/json

### 2. Get user by ID
GET http://localhost:8080/api/users/1
Accept: application/json

### 3. Get user by username
GET http://localhost:8080/api/users/username/john_doe
Accept: application/json

### 4. Create new user
POST http://localhost:8080/api/users
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "new_user",
  "email": "newuser@example.com",
  "password": "securepass123",
  "phone": "+15551234567",
  "address": "789 New Street, Boston, MA 02101",
  "enabled": true
}

### 5. Update user
PUT http://localhost:8080/api/users/1
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "john_doe_updated",
  "email": "john.doe.updated@example.com",
  "password": "newpassword123",
  "phone": "+15559876543",
  "address": "321 Updated Street, Seattle, WA 98101",
  "enabled": true
}

### 6. Delete user
DELETE http://localhost:8080/api/users/1

### 7. Get user statistics
GET http://localhost:8080/api/users/stats
Accept: application/json

### 8. Create user with validation error (short password)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/users
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "bad_user",
  "email": "baduser@example.com",
  "password": "123",
  "enabled": true
}

### 9. Create user with validation error (invalid email)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/users
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "bad_user2",
  "email": "invalid-email",
  "password": "password123",
  "enabled": true
}

### 10. H2 Console (Open in browser)
### http://localhost:8080/h2-console
### JDBC URL: jdbc:h2:mem:flywaydb
### Username: sa
### Password: (empty)
